,Recommended,291960,13049203,"Posted: 22 November, 2014",all,Pi,"Great game.I'm in the Uhlm Zahr hall.   Have invested about 100 hours in game play to date and have enjoyed every minute.100% chance I'll finish the game.    100% chance I'll play it again with different character classes.Every battle comes with anxiety and that is what makes it great.So many people complain about the maps.  Non issue.  A couple of dungeons in you get the Goblin map which has unlimited uses but can break.    I found myself traveling back to town often enough anyway that it was complete non-issue.Complaints about  early access reward not showing up in time .  Who cares.  Do you buy a game for early access reward or do you buy it for gaming experience?There are complaints about needing to grind in the early stages.  Not actually true.  You'll die more often and it's a touch harder to play dungeons after the 1st one without having done at least some grinding but is that really a negative?   Knowing you have to approach every battle like it's the last battle your party will ever have.  Is that truly a negative ?  I found it positive.   And if you find it a nuissance, you can choose to do the grinding.  At one juncture I did a couple of levels, is an hour or two.The game becomes more ""approachable"" once you get the Mage Diomente spell.  Allows you to teleport wherever you want.   Without it, it can get tediuos.  But given it's accessible for a Mage quite early, I don't see this as a negative either.Just plan your party reasonably and you'll be fine.My party which has died a very limited number of times:Innocent Characters:  Brawler, Samurai, Valkyrie, Mage.Between them I have 18 Diomente spells allowing me to complete dungeons without complaining about maps.  I quite literally bounce all over the maps as I like to do every square.The other two characters:Alchemist and Lord.    The Lord started as a Cleric.   Is a pretty lame character at this juncture.  Wish I had done something different - Cleric to Summoner comes to mind.   The Alchemist started as a Thief.   I don't miss the Thieving abilities.  I can open chests and my char investory is usually full before I use up all the High Portal spells.  I like the Alchemist Forging skill.I didn't bother with a Bishop for Identify and the dual spell casting - too much EXP needed to level up and money is plentiful.Overall - great game.  Thoroughly enjoyable gaming experince"
76561197993399611,Not Recommended,291960,28839729,"Posted: 30 December, 2016",all,.iko,"A faithful wizardry clone, but not actually a good game.I really badly wanted to like this game, it does a lot of things well, and it's really hard to find modern updates to the Wizardry formula. But it's just not good.The first big problem is that this is an intensely, intensely mechanics-driven game that is awful at explaining those mechanics. The entire game is translated from Japanese, and done so poorly. The in-game explanations for mechanics are usually vague or misleading, in a tiny scrolling 1-line box. The manual explains some things, but not nearly enough. At the same time, the game itself is wildly unbalanced. This is normally fine for this type of game, discovering abusive combinations and tricks is half the fun, but you basically can only figure things out through trial and error or going online for guides. A 'blind' playthrough, even for someone with huge amounts of RPG experience, would be practically unplayable. You can't just 'go with sounds good' because the game is intensely punishing for mistakes.That translation, combined with the natural vagueness of a wizardry clone, also makes questing an enormous pain in the♥♥♥♥♥ The interactions with the story and NPC's are incredibly vague: characters stand alone in dungeons and bark a short paragraph of vague, badly translated info at you, and then you're supposed to put 2 and 2 together and figure out what they need. If you forget what they said, you're kind of screwed. Again, this sort of stuff would be tolerable if the game was well made, well translated, with a good UI, but it's just not.Finally, this just isn't a well designed game. The dungeons are tedious, samey loops designed to be as drawn out as possible. The map system is really ill-considered, I'm actually fine with limiting map access, but this is like a weird worst of both worlds that just winds up being annoying. Character building is FILLED with lots of obscure mechanics that are impossible to know ahead of time without a guide and that can have a big impact. The game is incredibly random, literally in the sense of using random numbers, and forces the player to cope with that without giving them the knowledge to actually plan ahead and do so. The game relies immensely on grinding and repitition, but then has an absolutely awful UI to make that experience as lame as possible.It's just not a good game. I got this for $3 on a sale. For that price, it's fun and worth it if you like the genre. For the 10 dollar list price though, even at that cheap price, it's just not worth it. The only way you will like this game is if you really love intensely mechanics driven RPG's, know how to play Wizardries, and are willing to put up with a lot of ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥t. Even then, it's just not a good example of the genre."
76561198041931543,Recommended,291960,23512453,"Posted: 11 June, 2016",all,Otakatt,"I'm a huge fan of the older Wizardry games so when I saw this game I got my hopes up and... it hasn't disappointed. Elminage takes the oldschool grid dungeon crawl experience and adds a lot to it. There's a lot of variety in the dungeons and puzzles offered, the monster art, while sometimes peculiar, is gorgeous and really interesting to look at. I love the variety in classes and races you can play. Admittedly things were a little tedious before I got access to the mage's teleportation spell, but after that things went great.If you like what the oldschool sort of Wizardry games had to offer, this may very well be up your alley."
,Not Recommended,291960,16314432,"Posted: 11 June, 2015",all,Weisskaiser,"One of the greatest appeals of the Elminage series is being able to use your own portraits and music and such in the game. Elminage Gothic of course keeps up with this tradition. EXCEPT THAT THEY DECIDED TO REMOVE ALL OF IT FOR NO REASON IN THE PC VERSION. Do note that since the original version of the game was made with the ability to add your own stuff in mind, it comes with very few options by default. Well, you're stuck with those limited default options. Enjoy.The PC port is badly-done too (this was originally a PSP game), with everything looking hilarious oversized, and the localisation work is shoddy with a lot of falling back to NES era ""we can't fit all the text in so let's just make it all acronyms"". It's also odd how the nickname field doesn't have as many characters as the name fields which means you might want to have a character's nickname the same thing as their real name and straight up not be able to.I only got this because it was on sale at 294 yen, just a little over a tenth of what the lunatics are asking for on PSN (2571 yen), but the the near to 90% discount just simply doesn't outweigh the problems with this version.Very, VERY disappointing.That being said, you can run it in a small window if you like that sort of thing (watch videos on Youtube while dungeon crawling? Why not?) and the requirements are low enough that it runs fine on laptops so if you're looking for something to play on a flight or something this may be worth considering.The game itself is an alright Wizardry clone, except that Elminage 3 was better in literally every conceivable way (possibly because the series director who handled pretty much everything was fired halfway through 3's development process). Also the whole aging thing is weird."
